You can define multiple Apache Kafka topics by creating multiple NewTopic beans.
creating 10 topic:->
@Configuration
public class KafkaConfig {

    @Bean
    public NewTopic topic1() {
        return TopicBuilder.name("topic-1")
                .partitions(3)
                .replicas(1)
                .build();
    }

    @Bean
    public NewTopic topic2() {
        return TopicBuilder.name("topic-2")
                .partitions(3)
                .replicas(1)
                .build();
    }

    @Bean
    public NewTopic topic3() {
        return TopicBuilder.name("topic-3")
                .partitions(3)
                .replicas(1)
                .build();
    }

    // continue till topic10
}
But cleaner approach is:->
@Configuration
public class KafkaConfig {

    @Bean
    public KafkaAdmin.NewTopics topics() {
        return new KafkaAdmin.NewTopics(

                TopicBuilder.name("topic-1")
                        .partitions(3)
                        .replicas(1)
                        .build(),

                TopicBuilder.name("topic-2")
                        .partitions(3)
                        .replicas(1)
                        .build(),

                TopicBuilder.name("topic-3")
                        .partitions(3)
                        .replicas(1)
                        .build()

                // add remaining topics
        );
    }
}

Example:

kafkaTemplate.send("topic-1", message);

Here:

"topic-1" → identifies where message should go
Kafka broker routes the message to that topic

we can send:->
Only value
kafkaTemplate.send("topic-name", message);
Key + value
kafkaTemplate.send("topic-name", "user-1", message);

Key helps Kafka decide partition consistently.
So:
"topic-name" → Kafka topic
"user-1" → key
message → actual data/value

Why key is used:

Kafka uses the key to decide:

which partition the message should go to

Messages with same key usually go to same partition.

Example:

kafkaTemplate.send("orders", "customer-101", order1);
kafkaTemplate.send("orders", "customer-101", order2);
